David had a good phrase today: "on a bike trip you see the in-between". üòç
(From all the people you meet, not just those on bikes)
A huge part of these bike trips are the people you meet along the way. There is so much warmth, friendship, generosity, and shared humanity.
There is so much common experience but, also, I think having chosen to ride a long way alone means you share some similar outlooks.
It feels so comfortable talking to other people who've ridden by themselves. It was similar with Siri in Scotland and Sander in Norway.
We have gorged on pasta, bread, fruit, chocolate salami and biscuits. We chatted into the night about bike trips, life, running, people.
Tonight David and I visited a supermarket and bought lots of food and some beers. Then headed to a campsite (‚Ç¨4.20).
So, hopefully, I should get beyond Huelva tomorrow. That should keep me ahead of my rough schedule based on not having a proper route.
I decided to ride onwards with my new friend. We covered a good distance considering the late start. We passed beyond Faro.
A combination of not hearing back, worrying about how far I still had to cycle before my flight, and good company meant I took a decision.
It is funny how much you find in common with people doing big bike trips. So we rode on together. David passed his 1000 km milestone.
We went to a Lidl to get food and, comically, bought almost the same things. We sat outside on the ground eating and talking.
We rode together on the understanding that we could go our separate ways if we felt like it.
That was David, a cyclist from Barcelona, who had been cycling #Eurovelo1 along the coast of Portugal.
Then, not long after setting off I met another cyclist going the same way as me; we both got a bit lost in the one way system in Odi√°xere.
But I hadn't heard back from them in a few days so I suspected they might be busy with other stuff and I'd be imposing.  #britishproblems
I set off late because of expecting a shorter ride as I was going to stay with a friend of a friend before Faro.
Today did not go how it had been expected to. That is life on a bike trip. You adapt.
This demanding that I interact to a man's satisfaction doesn't happen as much to me as it does to women.
Not actively having a conversation with him meant I am some kind of recluse.
Who cares that I may just want a chance to rest after 11300 km of cycling?
Who cares that I have had conversations with almost everyone I've met for the past 115 days?
Who cares that I'd had a couple of conversations, in French, with the French people in the dormitory.
Just been "told off" by a Dutchman who was sharing my dormitory for not having said much to him. He generalised to me not being interactive.
Plus, bike repair shops will be harder to find. ;)
I wonder who will be the first to cycle around the Moon. They'll have less gravity and less rain but more issues with oxygen, water, & dust.

So I checked into a cheap hotel. I'm going to eat and rest. Hopefully the rash will go down.
My EHIC card means the only cost to me was Euro 4.40 for the prescription. They also told me to rest as the pills would make me drowsy.
But credit to the Spanish health service for seeing to me quickly, professionally, and kindly. You realise how lucky we are in Europe.
It is quite scary getting treatment when you can't really communicate because you don't know the language and people don't know yours.
The second doctor checked my blood pressure and I had a rest for a few minutes. She told me to take some juice or coffee with sugar.
I then went downstairs where I was given two injections in my buttocks. It was "Urbason". The second was quite painful and I got lightheaded
I joined a queue to see a doctor. I only had to wait 10 minutes. She prescribed an injection and some antihistamines for the next 5 days.
But we managed to clear that up and get to the right page in my passport showing I was from the EU.
I'm glad I had my EHIC card with me. The only confusion was my US travel visa as it looks like a photo page so they thought I was American.
I visited the local public health centre. Quite understandably, nobody really spoke English (or French). Google translate was our friend.
I'm hoping it is hives from the exertion of the past three days.
